         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">12/7/81 ¶  ¶ If all goes right, dear Sir Joseph, you will get by one of the next Steamers a Ward’s case with the three sp. of blue-flowering Andersonias from K.G. Sound. It would seem, that none of th...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.07.12a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 310.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; "/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Annotation</seg>: Sept 27th case arrived every plant — <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>utterly dead of [<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">course</hi>
                     </seg>] Such plants cannot stand transport in a Ward case [<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">illegible initials</seg>] Dr Mueller Informed same day.</p>
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">The entry in the Kew Inwards Book, 1878-1883, p. 332, 29 September 1881 (RBG Kew Kewensia)<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">records:<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Baron Mueller | Wardian case <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>| Several roots of grass-like plant in doubtful condition | Various species of Epacrideae ?Styphelia | all quite dead and rotten.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In J. Hooker to M, 25 September 1881, M was told that the plants arrived dead. The dates on the annotation and in the entry book given above are therefore not the dates the plants arrived, but the dates the entries were made.</p>
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>also M<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to [J. Hooker], 30 December 1881.</p>
               </note>12/7/81</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If all goes right, dear Sir Joseph, you will get by one of the next Steamers a Ward’s case with the three sp. of blue-flowering Andersonias from K.G. Sound. It would seem, that none of them got ever to Europe, though I had them in the Melbourne bot. Garden’s Green houses formerly. Mr Webb of Albany will send these remarkable plants at my expense, as I still am eager to take some little share in the introduction of new plants into Europe and also into Australia. If all goes right, the 3 species will be in bloom when they arrive, &amp; I should like very much that they be featured as the only Epacrids with<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">blue</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>corollas at once; for you might loose them; at all events they might not flower well with you next year. Of course, you could insert one plate in each of the three following numbers of the Magazine. I feel sure, you will do that for me, especially as this sending involves much trouble and expense to me, and as I like to keep my name before the horticultural world, “in spe”<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>in hope.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of better times also for me.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">It seems that hitherto only one species of the genus Andersonia was figured anywhere<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If the Ward’s case at all is returned, it ought to go to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">me</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>direct, so any return sendings for seeds from me.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I came across your letter printed here in 1876,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker to Under-Secretary of State, Foreign Office, 9 February 1876, published in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 8 May 1876. See also M to T. Wilson, 16 June 1881.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>but unfortunately the Phylloxera was here already then, being brought in ignorance of the Danger by a Swiss [V]ine<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>V <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">over</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>W<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(or<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>vice versa</seg>).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>planter when returning from a visit home. we try to eradicate the pest by uprooting the vines, and bisulphide of Carbon is tried, but I fear we must introduce American Vines for stock to graft on.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>the Phylloxera … visit<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">is marked in the margin with a line.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Andersonia</p>
         </div>
